\pard\f0\fs28 Trees, shrubs or herbs. Leaves alternate, rarely opposite, simple to 2-pinnate, stipulate. Flowers usually hermaphrodite, usually 5-merous.Sepals usually united. Petals free or somewhat connate. Stamens usually 10, sometimes less than 10 or numerous. Ovary a single unilocular carpel; style 1. Fruit a dehiscent, 2-valved or indehiscent, occasionally lomentaceous legume. Seeds usually without endosperm.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  A large number of species, both native and introduced, are cultivated for food, for fodder and for ornament. Those most frequently utilized as food are to be found in {\i Apios, Arachis, Cicer, Glycine, Glycyrrhiza, Lens, Phaseolus, Pisum, Vicia} and {\i Vigna.} The edible part is usually the seed or legume, or both. Species of these genera and many others, particularly in {\i Anthyllis, Ceratonia, Coronilla, Galega, Lathyrus, Lotus, Lupinus, Medicago, Melilotus, Trifolium} and{\i  Trigonella} are cultivated for fodder on a large scale or are planted to improve pasture.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Cultivated ornamental plants are to be found in the majority of European genera. In addition to some of those mentioned above, the following are of particular importance in this respect: {\i Acacia, Amorpha, Caragana, Cercis, Colutea, Cytisus} and{\i  Genista} and related genera, {\i Laburnum, Robinia, Sophora, Spartium} and {\i Wisteria}.
